  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This article, titled \"Rethinking how research is reviewed and published,\" will be featured in eLife in 2026, signaling a significant contribution to the discourse surrounding academic publishing practices.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The upcoming article titled \"Rethinking how research is reviewed and published,\" scheduled for publication in eLife in 2026, aims to address critical issues in the academic publishing landscape. This research recognizes the evolving demands for transparency, accessibility, and efficiency in the review process, vital elements in an era where collaboration and reproducibility have never been more important.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">One notable aspect of this work is the proven downstream reuse of its data and materials. This indicates that foundational research outputs have been effectively utilized in subsequent studies, reinforcing the significance of the insights offered in this article. Such reuse is a crucial marker of influence, as it reflects the applicability and relevance of the findings within the academic community.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In the growing conversation surrounding research methodologies, this article contributes to the discourse on how academic outputs can better serve both researchers and the public. By highlighting innovative approaches and practices, the authors advocate for a transformative shift in publication standards that align with contemporary scientific needs.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Ultimately, as this article progresses toward its release, it stands to inform future discussions and potentially reshape practices within the academic community. The framing of research review processes will have lasting implications not only for academics but also for the accessibility of knowledge in society at large.</p>",
